Let $\mathbf{a} = \begin{pmatrix} 7 \\ -4 \\ -4 \end{pmatrix}$ and $\mathbf{c} = \begin{pmatrix} -2 \\ -1 \\ 2 \end{pmatrix}.$  Find the vector $\mathbf{b}$ such that $\mathbf{a},$ $\mathbf{b},$ and $\mathbf{c}$ are collinear, and $\mathbf{b}$ bisects the angle between $\mathbf{a}$ and $\mathbf{c}.$

[asy]
unitsize(0.5 cm);

pair A, B, C, O;

A = (-2,5);
B = (1,3);
O = (0,0);
C = extension(O, reflect(O,B)*(A), A, B);

draw(O--A,Arrow(6));
draw(O--B,Arrow(6));
draw(O--C,Arrow(6));
draw(interp(A,C,-0.1)--interp(A,C,1.1),dashed);

label("$\mathbf{a}$", A, NE);
label("$\mathbf{b}$", B, NE);
label("$\mathbf{c}$", C, NE);
[/asy]

inference:
Since $\mathbf{a},$ $\mathbf{b},$ and $\mathbf{c}$ are collinear, $\mathbf{b}$ is a scalar multiple of $\mathbf{a}.$  Let $\mathbf{b} = k \mathbf{a}$ for some scalar $k.$

[asy]
unitsize(0.5 cm);

pair A, B, C, O;

A = (-2,5);
B = (1,3);
O = (0,0);
C = extension(O, reflect(O,B)*(A), A, B);

draw(O--A,Arrow(6));
draw(O--B,Arrow(6));
draw(O--C,Arrow(6));
draw(interp(A,C,-0.1)--interp(A,C,1.1),dashed);

label("$\mathbf{a}$", A, NE);
label("$\mathbf{b}$", B, NE);
label("$\mathbf{c}$", C, NE);
label("$k \mathbf{a}$", B, S);
[/asy]

Since $\mathbf{b}$ bisects the angle between $\mathbf{a}$ and $\mathbf{c},$
\[\frac{\mathbf{b}}{\|\mathbf{b}\|} = \frac{\mathbf{a} + \mathbf{c}}{\|\mathbf{a} + \mathbf{c}\|}.\]Then
\[\frac{k \mathbf{a}}{\|k \mathbf{a}\|} = \frac{\mathbf{a} + \mathbf{c}}{\|\mathbf{a} + \mathbf{c}\|}.\]Since $\|k \mathbf{a}\| = |k| \|\mathbf{a}\|,$
\[\frac{\mathbf{a}}{\|\mathbf{a}\|} = \frac{\mathbf{a} + \mathbf{c}}{\|\mathbf{a} + \mathbf{c}\|}.\]Then $\|\mathbf{a} + \mathbf{c}\| \mathbf{a} = \|\mathbf{a}\| (\mathbf{a} + \mathbf{c}).$  Hence,
\[(\|\mathbf{a} + \mathbf{c}\| - \|\mathbf{a}\|) \mathbf{a} = \|\mathbf{a}\| \mathbf{c}.\]We can compute
\begin{align*}
\|\mathbf{a} + \mathbf{c}\| &= \left\| \begin{pmatrix} 7 \\ -4 \\ -4 \end{pmatrix} + \begin{pmatrix} -2 \\ -1 \\ 2 \end{pmatrix} \right\| \\
&= \left\| \begin{pmatrix} 5 \\ -5 \\ -2 \end{pmatrix} \right\| \\
&= \sqrt{5^2 + (-5)^2 + (-2)^2} \\
&= \sqrt{54} \\
&= 3 \sqrt{6},
\end{align*}and
\[\|\mathbf{a}\| = \left\| \begin{pmatrix} 7 \\ -4 \\ -4 \end{pmatrix} \right\| = \sqrt{7^2 + (-4)^2 + (-4)^2} = 9.\]Then
\[(3 \sqrt{6} - 9) \begin{pmatrix} 7 \\ -4 \\ -4 \end{pmatrix} = 9 \begin{pmatrix} -2 \\ -1 \\ 2 \end{pmatrix}.\]This simplifies to
\[\begin{pmatrix} 21 \sqrt{6} - 63 \\ -12 \sqrt{6} + 36 \\ -12 \sqrt{6} + 36 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} -18 \\ -9 \\ 18 \end{pmatrix}.\]Hence, $21 \sqrt{6} - 63 = -18,$ so
\[k = \frac{-18}{21 \sqrt{6} - 63} = \frac{-6}{7 \sqrt{6} - 21} = \frac{-6 (7 \sqrt{6} + 21)}{(7 \sqrt{6} - 21)(7 \sqrt{6} + 21)} = \frac{-42 \sqrt{6} - 126}{42} = -\sqrt{6} - 3.\]Then
\[\mathbf{b} = (-\sqrt{6} - 3) \begin{pmatrix} 7 \\ -4 \\ -4 \end{pmatrix} = \boxed{\begin{pmatrix} -7 \sqrt{6} - 21 \\ 4 \sqrt{6} + 12 \\ 4 \sqrt{6} + 12 \end{pmatrix}}.\]I hope it is correct.

